docs.abstract: A partisan start to the trial stands in contrast to a consensus approach struck in 1999, the last time the Senate weighed the fate of a president.
docs.snippet: A partisan start to the trial stands in contrast to a consensus approach struck in 1999, the last time the Senate weighed the fate of a president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It is finally the Senate’s turn. And if recent history is any guide, President Trump’s impeachment trial will be an intensely partisan display that will make the polarization of the Clinton era look like a bygone period of political harmony.

headline.main: Its Reputation Tattered, Polarized Senate Faces a Steep Impeachment Test
headline.print_headline: A Bruised Chamber Is Unlikely to Rise Above Its Brawls

docs.abstract: Over nearly a year of tumultuous negotiations, congressional Democrats and the Trump administration bridged what seemed to be an impassable divide.
docs.snippet: Over nearly a year of tumultuous negotiations, congressional Democrats and the Trump administration bridged what seemed to be an impassable divide.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In the final days of negotiations over President Trump’s new North American trade deal, Robert Lighthizer, the top trade negotiator, made one more attempt to pressure House Democrats to get on board with the pact. He called Speaker Nancy Pelosi on Saturday saying he had booked a flight to Mexico to sign the revised trade agreement.

headline.main: How a Trump Trade Pact Won Over Democrats
headline.print_headline: An Unlikely Trade Pact, Forged Through Snacks and Sparring

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Lamar Alexander, Republican of Tennessee, said late Thursday that although he believed that Democrats had proved their case that President Trump acted “inappropriately” in his dealings with Ukraine, he did not think the president’s actions were impeachable and would vote against considering new evidence in the impeachment trial.
